The recoil protons were detected by a magnetic
spectrograph, equipped with four position-sensitive
drift chambers and three trigger scintillators. The
proton energy and emission angle was determined by
gamma-ray-tracing through the magnetic field.
The errors given are statistical errors only.
Systematic cross section scale uncertainty
The Gustaf Werner cyclotron at the
Svedberg laboratory, Uppsala University, was used.
A proton beam of 100 MeV impinged on a
100-200 mg/cm2 thick lithium target, enriched to
99.98% in 7-Li. The unaffected proton beam was bent
by a magnet into a well-shielded beam dump, while the
neutrons were collimated in a narrow cone at 0 degr.
by a heavy collimator system, before entering the
experimental area about 8 m after the production target
The neutron beam spot at the irradiation position had
a diameter of 7 cm. with a 5 microAmp beam, the neutron
yield at that position was about 1.0E+06 neutrons/sec
.The neutrons showed a semi-monoenergetic neutron
spectrum, with a full energy peak and a low-energy tail
The latter was suppressed by TOF and unfolding
techniques.
Five 120-410 mg/cm2 thick zirconium
targets, enriched to more than 99% in 90-Zr, were
mounted in a multitarget system with multiwire
proportional chambers between the targets. In this way
the energy loss in the subsequent targets could be
corrected for. In addition, a 50 mg/cm2 CH2 target was
mounted in the chamber for normalization purposes. At
angles larger than 15 degr., protons from reactions on
carbon in the target chamber foils can interfere with
the hydrogen peak in the ch2 spectrum, and a
84 mg/cm2 12-C target was used to correct for that.
Data obtained from N. Olsson.
